.TH PRINTF 3 "10 Jan 2026" "1.0" "Standard C Library"
.SH NAME
printf \- print formatted output to stdout
.SH SYNOPSIS
#include <stdio.h>

int printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fBprintf\fP function sends formatted output to \fBstdout\fP.

The \fBformat\fP string contains text to be written to \fBstdout\fP. It can optionally contain embedded format specifiers that are replaced by the values specified in additional arguments. 

Supported format specifiers include:
.TP
%c
Prints a single character.
.TP
%s
Prints a null-terminated string.
.TP
%d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
%u
Prints an unsigned decimal integer.
.TP
%o
Prints an unsigned octal number.
.TP
%x, %X
Prints an unsigned hexadecimal number (lowercase or uppercase).
.TP
%f
Prints a floating point number.
.TP
%%
Prints a literal percent sign.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, the total number of characters written is returned. On failure, a negative number is returned.

.SH ERRORS
If an output error occurs, a negative value is returned.

.SH EXAMPLE
The following example prints a formatted string to standard output:

.nf
printf("Hello, %s! You have %d new messages.\n", "Alice", 5);
.fi

.SH SEE ALSO
fprintf(3), sprintf(3), snprintf(3), dprintf(3)
